y 1395":"vóór 3 juli 1395","1330":"1330","Abt 1369":"circa 1369","1395":"1395","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","8 April 1415":"8 april 1415","Abt 1351":"circa 1351","1415":"1415","1325":"1325","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","before 1350":"vóór 1350","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"Abt 1351–8 April 1415":"about 1351–8 April 1415","1351–1415":"1351–1415","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1325–Male":"1325–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","Bef 3 July 1395":"before 3 July 1395","1330":"1330","Abt 1369":"about 1369","1395":"1395","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","8 April 1415":"8 April 1415","Abt 1351":"about 1351","1415":"1415","1325":"1325","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","before 1350":"before 1350","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan was born about 1351, in Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Fifhide, was 28 and her mother, Agnes Cowdray, was 23. She had at least 1 son with John Sandys. She died on 8 April 1415, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"Abt 1351–8 April 1415":"umbes 1351–8. aprill 1415","1351–1415":"1351–1415","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","Bef 3 July 1395":"enne 3. juulit 1395","1330":"1330","Abt 1369":"umbes 1369","1395":"1395","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","8 April 1415":"8. aprill 1415","Abt 1351":"umbes 1351","1415":"1415","1325":"1325","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","before 1350":"enne 1350","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1351–8 April 1415":"noin 1351–8. huhtikuuta 1415","1351–1415":"1351–1415","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1325–Male":"1325–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","Bef 3 July 1395":"ennen vuotta 3. heinäkuuta 1395","1330":"1330","Abt 1369":"noin 1369","1395":"1395","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","8 April 1415":"8. huhtikuuta 1415","Abt 1351":"noin 1351","1415":"1415","1325":"1325","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","before 1350":"ennen vuotta 1350","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"Abt 1351–8 April 1415":"environ 1351–8 avril 1415","1351–1415":"1351–1415","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1325–Male":"1325–Décédé","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","Bef 3 July 1395":"avant 3 juillet 1395","1330":"1330","Abt 1369":"environ 1369","1395":"1395","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","8 April 1415":"8 avril 1415","Abt 1351":"environ 1351","1415":"1415","1325":"1325","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","before 1350":"avant 1350","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hamp